Comment: Black wants to keep White from ganging up on the weakling at e5 with Nc3, Bg2 and Qc2, so this exchange, giving up the Bishop-pair, is almost mandatory lest Black bolt right out of the starting gate into a defensive and mostly passive box.

Black wants to open either the g- or h-file for his Rooks. The problem is that to do so he has to expose his King somewhat, and he needs his Bishop in that immediate neighborhood to help support his counterattack ...both of which factors White will soon exploit to his advantage.

Deserves at least a "!?" If Black takes the Rook then Be4 is followed by a quick Kg2 and Rh1+, and suddenly it's White who has a nasty attack for the Exchange. If 24. ...Qf3 then Black loses all the pressure he's tried to build up on the Kingside. And finally if 24. ...ef3?? 25. Qf5 wins. Objectively Black has one choice, and he plays it.
